        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>Pin</strong> is a saved piece of content on Pinterest that links back to a source URL. Pins can be images, videos, or product listings. Users discover them through Pinterest search or their home feed, and every Pin carries a clickable link to the original source — making Pinterest one of the few social platforms where content directly drives referral traffic over months or years rather than hours.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Platform</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Pinterest</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Traffic lifespan</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Months to years</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Best image ratio</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2:3 vertical</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Pinterest has over 500 million monthly active users, with 85% accessing via mobile. Unlike Instagram or TikTok posts that peak within hours, a well-optimized Pin can drive consistent referral traffic for years because it remains discoverable through Pinterest search and related content feeds indefinitely.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a Pin on Pinterest?</h2>
        <p>A Pin is the fundamental unit of content on Pinterest. Each Pin consists of:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>A visual</strong> — image, video, or GIF (vertical format performs best at 2:3 ratio)</li>
          <li><strong>A title</strong> — up to 100 characters, indexed by Pinterest search</li>
          <li><strong>A description</strong> — up to 500 characters, keyword-rich for discoverability</li>
          <li><strong>A destination URL</strong> — the link users follow when they click through</li>
          <li><strong>A board</strong> — the collection the Pin is saved to, which signals topical context</li>
        </ul>
        <p>When someone saves (or "repins") your Pin to their board, it extends the content's reach to their followers. This save-and-share mechanism is how Pins accumulate distribution over time — fundamentally different from the chronological feeds of Twitter or Instagram, where content disappears from visibility within hours.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Pinterest as a search engine</div>
          <p>Pinterest functions more like a visual search engine than a social network. Users come with high commercial intent — searching for "kitchen renovation ideas," "running gear for beginners," or "minimalist home office setup." Pins that rank well in Pinterest search drive consistent, intent-qualified traffic to source URLs.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Pins matter for marketing</h2>
        <p>Pins are one of the few social media assets with a compounding traffic profile. Three reasons they matter commercially:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Long content lifespan.</strong> An Instagram post drives traffic for 24-48 hours. A well-optimized Pin can drive clicks for months or years through Pinterest search, related Pins, and board discovery. The content investment pays dividends long after it's published.</li>
          <li><strong>High purchase intent audience.</strong> Pinterest reports that 87% of users have purchased a product because of Pinterest. The platform attracts users actively planning — home renovations, weddings, recipes, wardrobes — making it especially effective for ecommerce and lifestyle brands.</li>
          <li><strong>Referral traffic with zero algorithm dependency.</strong> Each Pin carries a direct link to the source. When users click, they arrive at your site. Unlike organic social reach that fluctuates with algorithm changes, Pin traffic comes from search behavior and saves — more stable and predictable than feed-dependent platforms.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Pins work in practice</h2>
        <p>Pinterest's distribution mechanism works in three stages:</p>

        <h3>Stage 1 — Initial indexing</h3>
        <p>When you publish a Pin, Pinterest indexes the visual content, title, description, and destination URL. Pinterest's image recognition system categorizes the visual; the description and title provide keyword signals for search ranking. A Pin linking to a URL with relevant metadata (title tags, OG data) gets additional context from the source page.</p>

        <h3>Stage 2 — Discovery and saves</h3>
        <p>Pins surface through Pinterest Search, the home feed (personalized to each user's interests), the "More like this" section below other Pins, and shopping surfaces for Product Pins. When users save a Pin to their boards, it appears in their followers' feeds, extending distribution. High-save Pins get amplified by Pinterest's algorithm as quality signals accumulate.</p>

        <h3>Stage 3 — Long-tail search traffic</h3>
        <p>Unlike social posts, Pins rank in Pinterest search for weeks and months after publication. A Pin about "fall living room decor ideas" published in September may rank for related searches through December and resurface again the following autumn. This seasonal compounding is unique to Pinterest's search-driven architecture.</p>

