        <h2 id="examples">Real Pin marketing examples</h2>

        <h3>1. DTC skincare brand — format testing</h3>
        <p>A skincare brand tested five different Pin formats over 30 days for the same product. Infographic-style Pins showing "before/after skincare routines" drove 3x more saves and shares than standard product photography Pins. The top-performing format reshaped their entire content calendar — shifting 60% of Pin production to educational infographic content.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B consultant — LinkedIn vs Pinterest parallel test</h3>
        <p>A B2B consultant who focused on LinkedIn expanded to Pinterest with infographic versions of their frameworks. Pinterest Pins targeting "business strategy templates" and "marketing frameworks" drove 400 monthly clicks within 90 days — a low volume but entirely incremental, adding to rather than cannibalizing existing channel traffic.</p>

        <h3>3. Local restaurant — seasonal content strategy</h3>
        <p>A local restaurant published seasonal recipe Pins linking to their catering inquiry page ("fall dinner party menu ideas," "holiday catering for 50 people"). Competitor restaurants with no Pinterest presence missed this discovery channel entirely. The restaurant built 15,000 followers over 18 months and consistently drove catering inquiries from organic Pin traffic.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Pins vs other social content — what's different</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Pins (Pinterest)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Lifespan: months to years</li>
              <li>Discovery: search-driven</li>
              <li>Traffic: direct referral via URL</li>
              <li>Audience: high purchase intent</li>
              <li>Content: visual, reference-based</li>
              <li>Best for: evergreen content, products</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Posts (Instagram, TikTok, X)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Lifespan: hours to days</li>
              <li>Discovery: feed and algorithm-driven</li>
              <li>Traffic: limited link-out (Instagram especially)</li>
              <li>Audience: broader, less purchase-intent</li>
              <li>Content: real-time, trend-reactive</li>
              <li>Best for: brand awareness, community</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for Pins that drive traffic</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Use vertical images at 2:3 ratio (1000x1500px).</strong> Pinterest's mobile-first feed prioritizes vertical content. Horizontal or square Pins take up less screen space and receive less engagement. The 2:3 ratio is the platform standard.</li>
          <li><strong>Add keyword-rich text overlay to the image.</strong> Pinterest's image recognition reads text in images. A text overlay that describes the Pin's value ("5 Kitchen Renovation Ideas Under $500") helps both algorithm classification and human scroll-stopping.</li>
          <li><strong>Write a keyword-rich description (150-300 characters).</strong> Pinterest search ranks Pins based on description text. Include 2-3 relevant keywords naturally. Don't keyword-stuff — write for the person who will read it.</li>
          <li><strong>Link to a specific, relevant destination.</strong> Don't link every Pin to your homepage. Link to the specific blog post, product page, or landing page that delivers the value the Pin promises. Mismatched landing pages increase bounce rates and reduce Pin quality scores.</li>
          <li><strong>Save consistently — 5-10 Pins per day.</strong> Pinterest's algorithm rewards consistent publishing over sporadic bursts. Use a scheduling tool (Tailwind, Buffer) to maintain a daily cadence without requiring daily manual effort.</li>
          <li><strong>Organize boards by topic, not by content type.</strong> A board called "Blog Posts" doesn't help users or Pinterest's algorithm. A board called "Small Kitchen Renovation Ideas" does both — it tells users exactly what they'll find and gives Pinterest keyword context for all Pins in that board.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common Pin mistake — not optimizing the destination page</div>
          <p>A high-performing Pin drives clicks; those clicks hit your website. If the landing page is slow, irrelevant, or fails to deliver the value the Pin promised, users bounce immediately. Pinterest measures downstream engagement — pages with high bounce rates from Pin traffic receive less distribution over time. Optimize Pin and landing page together.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Pin mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Horizontal or square images</strong> — they get less feed real estate and lower engagement on mobile.</li>
          <li><strong>No text overlay</strong> — images without descriptive text miss both human attention and algorithm classification.</li>
          <li><strong>Linking to the homepage</strong> — generic landing pages produce high bounce rates and lower Pin quality scores.</li>
          <li><strong>Keyword-free descriptions</strong> — without search keywords, Pins rely only on saves for distribution, not search traffic.</li>
          <li><strong>Irregular publishing</strong> — gaps of weeks between Pins reset algorithm momentum; consistency matters.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring Product Pins for ecommerce</strong> — Product Pins pull live pricing and availability and appear in Pinterest Shopping surfaces, driving direct purchase traffic.</li>
        </ul>

